# Ignore-rect mask for settings_smoke (NumOS SDL2 emulator visual test).
#
# Reason: the ONLY volatile region on the SettingsApp screen across separate
# launches is the StatusBar clock. SettingsApp has NO blinking input cursor and no
# animation once its 200 ms fade-in settles, so the body (toggles, precision, etc.)
# is byte-stable. The clock label is drawn by StatusBar::updateClock() from the
# real wall clock (time() -> localtime -> "%02d:%02d", src/ui/StatusBar.cpp), so
# HH:MM reflects the minute each scripted run happens to execute on. Two launches
# in different minutes (or hours) therefore differ only inside the clock glyphs.
# This is expected per-minute UI nondeterminism, NOT a renderer bug — the renderer
# is frozen, so it is masked in the comparator instead of edited in src/.
#
# Region: the clock label is aligned LV_ALIGN_LEFT_MID,6 in lv_font_montserrat_12
# (StatusBar.cpp:61-65) and is always exactly 5 glyphs ("HH:MM"), so its box spans
# ~x[6..38] y[8..16]. A back-to-back jitter diff across a minute rollover
# (compare-ppm.py A B --write-diff) put the changed pixels at x[31..37] y[8..16]
# (the minute-units digit). Because the HOUR digits can also change between
# arbitrary launches, the mask must cover the WHOLE label, not just the minutes.
#
# Rect = full HH:MM label box (~x[6..38] y[8..16]) padded ~2px on each side ->
# x[4..40] y[6..18]. This is tight to the clock: the app title is centered
# (x~160), the modifier/angle/battery are right-aligned (x>240), and the app body
# is below the y=24 StatusBar separator — none are masked.
#
# x,y,w,h
4,6,37,13
